fields.name: fishing
fields.description: The Portal will be collecting and integrating data on the productive habitats and rich species diversity that are essential for maintaining healthy fishing areas.

fields.name: security
fields.description: The Mid-Atlantic is home to important naval installations and training areas, and it’s a busy corridor for commercial shipping and naval and other defense and security operations.

fields.name: maritime-industries
fields.description: The Mid-Atlantic ports are some of the busiest in the nation’s seaport network, which unloads $3.8 billion in goods each day.

fields.name: energy
fields.description: Offshore wind in the Mid-Atlantic holds more than 60,000 Megawatts of potential energy — that’s 10% of total U.S. offshore potential. This huge resource could help meet the growing electricity demand in the region, while reducing carbon emissions.

fields.name: Major Canyons
fields.description: This data layer represents major canyons of the Mid-Atlantic Coast. These boundaries were created primarily for cartographic purposes and do not represent ecological boundaries.

fields.name: OCS Boundaries
fields.description: Administrative Boundaries extending from the Submerged Lands Act Boundary seaward to the limit of the United States Outer Continental Shelf (The U.S. 200 nautical mile limit, or other marine boundary).

fields.name: Artificial Reefs
fields.description: These are polygon locations of Mid-Atlantic artificial reefs. They were compiled from various state sources.

fields.name: Protraction Boundaries
fields.description: This data set contains Official Protraction Diagram (OPD) outlines.

fields.name: Endangered Whales
fields.description: Sightings for each ten minute square were divided by the effort for each ten minute square to calculate Sightings Per Unit Effort (SPUE).

fields.name: Fishing Effort
fields.description: This is an extract of Fishing Vessel Trip Report (FVTR) data that The Nature Conservancy compiled from raw data received from the National Marine Fisheries Service (NMFS).

fields.name: Marine Jurisdictions
fields.description: The Marine Jurisdiction data set is a standardized compilation of published marine boundaries from the NOAA Office of Coast Survey and the Minerals Management Service.

fields.name: Waterbird Survey
fields.description: This data layer contains waterbird density blocks extracted from the Minerals Management Service's Mid-Atlantic Waterbird Data Beta Version 1.0. (2001-2003)

fields.name: All Gear Types
fields.description: This is an extract of Fishing Vessel Trip Report (FVTR) data that The Nature Conservancy compiled from raw data received from the National Marine Fisheries Service (NMFS).

fields.name: Bottom Gear Types
fields.description: This is an extract of Fishing Vessel Trip Report (FVTR) data that The Nature Conservancy compiled from raw data received from the National Marine Fisheries Service (NMFS).

fields.name: Pelagic Gear Types
fields.description: This is an extract of Fishing Vessel Trip Report (FVTR) data that The Nature Conservancy compiled from raw data received from the National Marine Fisheries Service (NMFS).

fields.name: Summer Flounder Landings
fields.description: This is an extract of Fishing Vessel Trip Report (FVTR) data that The Nature Conservancy compiled from raw data received from the National Marine Fisheries Service (NMFS).

fields.name: Wind Energy Areas
fields.description: WEAs are offshore locations that appear most suitable for wind energy development.

fields.name: Submarine Cables
fields.description: This represents cables that have been laid underwater or buried beneath the seabed.

fields.name: Sediment Grain Size
fields.description: The Nature Conservancy developed this science-based ecoregional assessment for the Northwest Atlantic Marine region (Bay of Fundy to Cape Hatteras, North Carolina). This assessment synthesizes information on oceanography, chemistry, geology, biology, and social science to inform decisions about coastal and marine ecosystems.

fields.name: Essential Fish Habitat
fields.description: Essential Fish Habitat (EFH) is defined as those waters and substrate necessary to fish for spawning, breeding, feeding, or growth to maturity (16 U.S.C. 1802(10)).

fields.name: Seabed Form
fields.description: Seabed forms classify seafloor topography into discrete units. Derived from The Nature Conservancy's derived digital bathymetry, seabed forms can be described by a combination of just two variables: seabed position and slope.

fields.name: Wind Speed
fields.description: Annual average wind speeds are closely related to the available energy at a particular location and are categorized in these data by their value at a height of 90 meters above the surface.

fields.name: OCS Lease Blocks
fields.description: Outer Continental Shelf (OCS) lease blocks and administrative boundaries are generated to define small geographic areas that identify federal land ownership and support offshore resource management.

fields.name: Turtles --Sightings per Unit Effort (SPUE)
fields.expected_date: As soon as vetted by Portal Data Review Team
fields.notes: Need to add summary SPUE grid for all three species assessed (green, leatherback and Atlantic loggerhead turtles) across seasons.
fields.source: "TNC NAM ERA compiled data;  source of data U.S. Navy Marine Resource Assessment (MRA) for the Northeast and Virginia Capes"
fields.description: Important areas for sea turtles were determined from point sightings data. Data were assessed, combined and converted from seasonal species sightings into ten minute squares and effort-corrected.  The resulting sightings per unit effort (SPUE) grids were used to identify important areas within the region for each species.

fields.name: Coldwater coral locations
fields.notes: Points represent only where corals were observed.  The absence of a point does not necessarily indicate the absence of corals.
fields.description: Known point locations on coldwater corals and associated taxonomic information in Mid-Atlantic

fields.name: Marine Mammals--Sightings per Unit Effort (SPUE)
fields.expected_date: As soon as vetted by Portal Data Review Team
fields.notes: Need to add summary data layers with SPUE grids combined for multiple species and seasons (e.g. all toothed whales).  Assessed species include include fin whale, humpback whale, minke whale, northern Atlantic right whale, sperm whale, sei whale, Atlantic whitesided dolphin, bottlenose dolphin, harbor porpoise, and Atlantic striped dolphin.
fields.source: "TNC NAM ERA compiled data;  source of data U.S. Navy Marine Resource Assessment (MRA) for the Northeast and Virginia Capes"
fields.description:
"Important areas for marine mammals were
determined from point sightings data. Data were assessed, combined and converted from seasonal species sightings into ten minute squares and effort-corrected. The resulting sightings per unit effort (SPUE) grids were used to identify important areas within the region for each species."
